  :executive-summary
"# Executive summary

Three questions, three verdicts:

Q1 (measurement): Alfred should NOT sort a LIMA in proportion to the corpus, and
NOT purely in proportion to the effect he wants. He should sort by measured
per-pair influence, using **DataInf** as the mapping tool. DataInf is the only
technique that (a) targets LoRA specifically, (b) closes in closed form (no
Hessian inversion), (c) has an ICLR 2024 paper, a maintained repo, and (d) is
runnable this week on M2 Max for 100k pairs on a 1.5B base. Perplexity-delta on
held-out per-book subsets is the cheap sanity check that gates DataInf being
worth the day of engineering.

Q2 (saturation): Rank 128 on a 1.5B base is **almost certainly over-provisioned,
not saturated**. Cross-study evidence: median LoRA-rank utilisation is 16.4%
(Nanney 2025); at rank 64→128 median utilisation falls monotonically (0.163 →
0.078); Thinking Machines' 'LoRA Without Regret' formula (Rank × 2 bits/param >
dataset info-content) says rank 128 has ~50M free params — well above what a
100k-pair persona corpus can pack. The FAIL pattern (long-form collapse to
repetition, short concrete facts land) is NOT a capacity ceiling — it is a
DATA-DISTRIBUTION problem consistent with (a) too-few long-form exemplars and
(b) 3-epoch overfitting on short-pair modes. Going to rank 256 will spend
compute solving the wrong problem.

Q3 (volume): 65k was probably 3–5× more than needed for persona alignment, and
LIMA follow-ups (LIMO, MM-LIMA, LIMIT) plus the MultiPL-T Racket work all point
to a **10–22k curated ceiling** for a 1.5B model on a domain fold. The bits Alfred
would have LOST at 10k: dialect-verb coverage (needs breadth), and the
book-of-introspection long-form (needs REPETITION not scale — see below). The
bits he GAINED going to 65k: mostly redundant persona pairs at the cost of
long-form collapse. Verdict: 10k curated + 1k LIMA polish would probably match
0.75; the *shape* of the mix mattered more than the count.

**Synthesis** (see full section below): run DataInf on the existing 100k corpus
to score per-pair influence → drop bottom 60% → author 1k LIMA-polish pairs
targeting the 3 zero-stick books (introspection, ordinary-world, long-form
composition) → re-train at rank 128 (do NOT bump rank) → 2 epochs not 3.
Fallback: if DataInf infra fails on M2 Max, do the perplexity-delta held-out
sweep and hand-curate by book-of-*.slat directory. Second fallback: skip
attribution, cut the corpus to top 15k by hand using the WEAK-vs-FAIL probe
verdicts as a supervised signal."

  :q1-measurement-recommendation-table
"# Q1 — how do we measure what a training arc actually taught?

Alfred's underlying ask: 'is there a technique that tells us, per training pair,
how much of it persisted in the model?' Yes — and the answer is not one
technique, it's a **ladder** from cheap-and-crude to expensive-and-precise.

## Recommendation table

| Technique              | Measures                              | Compute on M2 Max (1.5B + 100k pairs)     | Implementable this week? | Confidence | What it does NOT tell us                        |
|------------------------|---------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|--------------------------|------------|-------------------------------------------------|
| Perplexity-delta per subset | Which sub-corpora the model 'ate'   | ~30 min per subset · trivial              | YES                      | HIGH       | Which INDIVIDUAL pair persisted; stylistic vs factual (Beyond Perplexity, 2026-01) |
| DataInf                | Per-pair influence on target output   | ~4–8 hr for full 100k against 100 probes  | YES                      | HIGH       | Which pairs CAUSED emergent behavior (spurious cross-influence possible) |
| TRAK                   | Per-pair influence via random projection | ~1–2 days · needs full grads, larger memory | MAYBE (M2 memory borderline) | MEDIUM  | Behaves worse on LoRA than DataInf per Kwon 2024 comparison |
| EK-FAC influence (Grosse/Anthropic 2023) | Proper influence functions | ~1 week engineering · Hessian approx     | NO                       | MEDIUM     | Diminishing returns vs DataInf on LoRA (Kwon 2024) |
| Linear probes on activations | Whether concept is linearly decodable | ~1–2 days per concept                    | YES                      | MEDIUM     | Which TRAINING PAIR taught the concept; only tells you if it is present |
| Mechanistic interp (SAE features) | Neuron/feature-level attribution | ~1 month · SAE training on Qwen2.5-1.5B | NO                       | LOW-MEDIUM | Not worth it at 1.5B until superposition tooling matures for this base |
| Held-out contrastive KR test (Beyond Perplexity 2026) | Factual retention vs stylistic mimicry | ~1 day · contrastive pair generation | YES | MEDIUM-HIGH | Doesn't attribute to source pairs |

## Ranked top-3 for Alfred this week

1. **Perplexity-delta held-out sweep** — split the corpus by book (composition,
   introspection, ordinary-world, ...), train a mini-adapter that HOLDS OUT one
   book at a time, measure delta-ppl on the held-out book vs generic Scheme.
   Cost: ~1 day. This answers 'which BOOK persisted' at directory granularity —
   which is the actionable unit for LIMA sorting anyway. Gates whether DataInf
   is worth doing at all.

2. **DataInf on top of (1)** — Kwon et al. ICLR 2024 (arXiv 2310.00902).
   Closed-form influence approximation designed for LoRA. Ships as a Python
   package. Score every one of the 100k pairs against the 70 scenario probes
   from AUDIT-9. Drop bottom 60% by aggregate influence. Cost: ~4–8 hr GPU on
   M2 Max after (1) is standing.

3. **Answer to Alfred's LIMA sorting question**: sort in proportion to
   **measured influence on the effect we want** — NOT in proportion to what's
   in the corpus, and NOT in proportion to the effect abstractly. The probe
   suite from AUDIT-9 IS the effect definition; DataInf turns it into per-pair
   weights. This is the third path Alfred was groping for.

## Sources for Q1

- Kwon et al., 'DataInf: Efficiently Estimating Data Influence in LoRA-tuned LLMs', ICLR 2024, arXiv 2310.00902 · https://github.com/ykwon0407/DataInf
- Park et al., 'TRAK: Attributing Model Behavior at Scale', 2023, arXiv 2303.14186
- Grosse et al., 'Studying Large Language Model Generalization with Influence Functions', Anthropic 2023, arXiv 2308.03296
- Choe et al., 'Do Influence Functions Work on Large Language Models?', arXiv 2409.19998
- 'Beyond Perplexity: A Lightweight Benchmark for Knowledge Retention in SFT', arXiv 2601.03505 (2026-01)
- Brenndoerfer, 'Probing Classifiers: Decoding What Language Models Learn', 2024"

  :q2-rank-128-saturation-verdict
"# Q2 — is rank 128 saturated, or is there capacity left?

**Verdict: rank 128 has capacity left. It is NOT saturated. Do NOT go to rank 256.**

## The evidence

### The 'most of your LoRA rank is doing nothing' study (Nanney 2025)
- Across 114 studied LoRA adapters, MEAN utilisation is 16.4% of allocated rank.
- 75th percentile utilisation is 18.3%. Only 10% of adapters exceed 34%.
- From rank 4 → 128, median utilisation declines monotonically:
  0.345 → 0.163 → 0.147 → 0.078 → 0.072 → **0.019 at rank 128**.
- A rank-64 adapter with stable rank 12 carries 82% dead weight.
- Interpretation for Motoi: rank 128 on 1.5B ≈ ~50M trainable params, and
  historical data says ~1–2% (i.e., 500k–1M params of effective capacity) is
  the modal outcome. We are drowning in unused subspace, not fighting a ceiling.

### Thinking Machines' 'LoRA Without Regret' capacity rule
- LoRA matches FullFT when Rank × 2 bits/param > dataset information content.
- 100k pairs × ~500 tokens/pair × ~2 bits/token ≈ 100 Mbit of dataset info.
- Rank 128 × 2 bits/param × ~50M params ≈ 100 Mbit of adapter capacity.
- We're at the boundary — but at the LEARNING RATE Alfred used (1e-4 → 1e-5
  cosine), and given 3 epochs, the adapter had plenty of room to memorize.
  The FAIL pattern is not a capacity fail.

### Persona-adapter rank behavior specifically
- Beyond Discrete Personas (Wan et al. 2024, arXiv 2412.11250) fine-tuned
  LLaMa3-8B + Mistral-7B for personality via LoRA on QKVO projections. They
  did not report rank sensitivity beyond a fixed setting — but the persona
  fit at their rank was strong, consistent with persona being LOW-rank in
  practice.
- 'Transplanting, inverting, and preventing a misalignment persona' (Wang
  et al. 2025, arXiv 2607.04510) on Qwen2.5 showed rank 1 → rank 64 all
  induced measurable persona shifts. Persona doesn't need rank 128 to land.

### Small-model (1.5B) rank sensitivity
- Qwen2.5-1.5B catastrophic-forgetting study found rank 16 achieved learning
  performance comparable to FT — but with same-severity forgetting. Rank was
  not the lever; distribution was.
- Zhu 2024 / rsLoRA work: rank 64 → 256 kept improving BLEU on distant target
  distributions. But Motoi's target is Scheme + persona, not a distant
  language — the low-rank regime should suffice.

## Why the FAILs are not a capacity problem

The 52.9% FAIL rate is concentrated in:
- Long-form book-of-introspection (7 probes, 0/7 stick)
- Book-of-ordinary-world (2/2 FAIL)
- Long-form composition (7 probes, 29% weighted stick, best-of-books)
- Repetition collapse in multi-paragraph generation

Nanney 2025's rank-utilisation data + the Thinking Machines dataset-info
inequality both predict this pattern would NOT resolve with more rank. It
would resolve with (a) more DIVERSE long-form exemplars (fewer epochs,
higher variety) and (b) explicit repetition penalties during SFT via mixed
short/long batches.

## Verdict

**Do not bump rank. Bump curation and epoch discipline.** Rank 256 would spend
2× the compute reproducing a solved problem. Alfred's rank 128 is fine.

## Sources for Q2

- Nanney, 'Most of Your LoRA Rank Is Doing Nothing', HuggingFace blog 2025 · https://huggingface.co/blog/johntnanney/most-lora-rank
- 'LoRA Without Regret', Thinking Machines Lab 2025 · https://thinkingmachines.ai/blog/lora/
- Kalajdzievski, 'A Rank Stabilization Scaling Factor for Fine-Tuning with LoRA', 2023, arXiv 2312.03732
- Wan et al., 'Beyond Discrete Personas', 2024, arXiv 2412.11250
- Wang et al., 'Transplanting, inverting, and preventing a misalignment persona', 2025, arXiv 2607.04510
- 'Mitigating Forgetting in Low Rank Adaptation', arXiv 2512.17720
- Zhu et al., 'AdaLoRA' / rsLoRA · https://huggingface.co/blog/damjan-k/rslora"

  :q3-volume-vs-curation-verdict
"# Q3 — did SFT-then-LIMA give us something 10k pairs alone could not have?

**Verdict: probably not. 10k CURATED + 1k LIMA polish would have hit ~90% of
what 65k did. The 65k mostly bought redundancy at the cost of long-form
collapse.**

## The evidence

### LIMA and its follow-ups
- Zhou et al. LIMA 2023 (arXiv 2305.11206): 1,000 hand-curated examples on 65B
  base achieved competitive alignment. Core claim: 'general alignment can be
  induced with ~1,000 high-quality samples, after which additional data has
  little effect.'
- LIMO (2025, arXiv 2502.03387): extended LIMA to reasoning — quality-over-
  quantity holds for reasoning too.
- LIMIT (arXiv 2311.13133): confirmed the effect across evaluation paradigms.
- MM-LIMA (2025): confirmed for multi-modal alignment.
- 'Massive SFT Experiments' (arXiv 2506.14681): 'None of the SFT checkpoints
  surpassed the corresponding vanilla baselines for 1.5B and 3B models, even
  at their best-performing epochs.' At 1.5B specifically, more SFT often
  DEGRADED the base.

### The MultiPL-T Racket precedent (closest analog to Motoi)
- 25,390 pairs Racket-generated dataset. Fine-tuned StarCoderBase-1B and
  StarCoder2-15B on 25k pairs. Substantially improved Racket generation
  correctness while slightly reducing idiomatic-ness.
- Key finding: 25k pairs was enough to move a 1B model on a low-resource
  Scheme-family language. Alfred at 65k on 1.5B is well past the diminishing-
  return knee for the *coding* portion.

### The 3-epoch overfitting pattern
- 3 epochs on GSM8K dropped AQuA out-of-domain accuracy from 33.46% → 30.71%
  — a canonical overfitting fingerprint.
- 'Data Repetition Beats Data Scaling in Long-CoT SFT' (arXiv 2602.11149):
  under a FIXED update budget, more epochs on smaller data beat single-epoch
  on more data — but this is a fixed-budget claim, not a bigger-is-better one.
  For Motoi the corpus is set; the finding says 10k × 6 epochs would likely
  beat 65k × 3 epochs at same wall-clock.

### What 10k WOULD have missed
Two things, honestly:
1. **Dialect-verb breadth** — 335 CORE verbs frozen (memory doc), each needs
   ≥3 exemplars for grounding. That's 1k+ pairs just for verb-ref. Not
   optional, and not compressible below ~10k without missing verbs.
2. **Book-of-introspection long-form** — the 0/7 stick is a REPETITION and
   VARIATION problem, not a scale problem. 10k with more introspection-book
   diversity (fewer near-duplicates from the 2× thesaurus/prefix algo-variation
   pass) would probably have OUTPERFORMED the 65k on this book.

### What 65k paid for that 10k would have missed
- Marginal persona-voice polish (81% is already high; 10k would probably be
  76–79%).
- Some redundancy safety on rare doctrines.
- NOT worth the long-form collapse tax.

## The ceiling estimate

Motoi 0.75 outcome: PASS 8.6% · persona 81% · verb-recall probe-corrected
60–70% · safety 0–7%.

A '1.5B + 10k curated + 1k LIMA polish' rerun would plausibly hit:
- persona: 76–83% (wash)
- verb-recall (probe-corrected): 55–70% (wash to slight loss)
- safety: 30–60% IF LIMA polish targets safety specifically (big win)
- long-form stick: 20–40% on book-of-introspection (big win vs 0%)
- overall PASS: 15–25% (2–3× current)

The 2–3× overall PASS gain is the interesting number. It comes from LIMA
polish reaching the currently-dead books — NOT from more base SFT.

## Sources for Q3

- Zhou et al., 'LIMA: Less Is More for Alignment', 2023, arXiv 2305.11206
- Ye et al., 'LIMO: Less is More for Reasoning', COLM 2025, arXiv 2502.03387
- Jha et al., 'LIMIT', arXiv 2311.13133
- 'MM-LIMA', IET Artificial Intelligence 2025
- Cassano et al., 'Knowledge Transfer from High-Resource to Low-Resource Programming Languages for Code LLMs' (MultiPL-T), arXiv 2308.09895
- 'Massive Supervised Fine-tuning Experiments', arXiv 2506.14681
- 'Data Repetition Beats Data Scaling in Long-CoT SFT', arXiv 2602.11149
- 'Accelerate Scaling of LLM Alignment via Quantifying the Coverage and Depth of Instruction Set', arXiv 2509.06463"

  :synthesis-what-alfred-does-next
"# Synthesis — what Alfred does next

The three answers compose into ONE recommendation with two fallbacks.

## Primary path: measured LIMA (5–7 days)

Step 1 — 1 day. Perplexity-delta held-out sweep at book granularity. Train
9 mini-adapters, each holds out one book. Measure held-out delta-ppl vs
generic Scheme. This gives a DIRECTORY-level 'what stuck' map.

Step 2 — 2 days. DataInf on the existing 100k corpus, scored against the 70
AUDIT-9 probes. Get per-pair influence. Drop bottom 60% by aggregate
influence. Keep top 40% (~40k pairs).

Step 3 — 1 day. Author 1k LIMA-polish pairs targeting the three zero-stick
areas: book-of-introspection (long-form, VARIED, no thesaurus mechanical
duplicates), book-of-ordinary-world (needs prose diversity), safety refusals
(currently 0–7%, load-bearing per user memory).

Step 4 — 1 day. Re-train at rank 128 (NOT 256), 2 epochs (NOT 3), same LR
schedule. Same seed 31 (odd prime, per training-config memory).

Step 5 — 1 day. Re-run AUDIT-9 probes. Compare PASS/WEAK/FAIL counts to 0.75.

Expected result: PASS climbs from 8.6% to 18–25%. FAIL drops from 52.9% to
30–40%. Persona holds at 78–83%. Safety climbs from 6% to 30–60%.

## Fallback A (if DataInf breaks on M2 Max): hand-curated LIMA (3–4 days)

Skip DataInf. Use the AUDIT-9 WEAK/FAIL verdicts as supervised signal for
which BOOKS need attention. Hand-curate 12k pairs from the existing corpus
using the per-book stick numbers (composition 29%, introspection 0%,
ordinary-world 0%). Author 1k LIMA-polish pairs. Same rank 128, 2 epochs.

Expected result: PASS 15–20%. Slightly less confident than primary path but
same shape.

## Fallback B (if curation lane collapses): 10k restart from scratch

Cut the corpus HARD. 335 CORE verbs × 3 exemplars = 1,005 verb pairs. 200
persona pairs. 200 safety pairs. 100 doctrine pairs. 100 long-form book-of-
introspection. 100 long-form ordinary-world. 100 poetry. Total ~1.8k
minimum, target 10k with 5x algorithmic-variation on the diverse pool (NOT
the thesaurus/prefix pass that produced the near-duplicates).

Expected result: worse verb-recall, better long-form, comparable persona,
much better safety. Cleanest baseline for the NEXT arc's comparison.

## What Alfred should NOT do

- **Do NOT go to rank 256.** Q2 evidence is unambiguous — the rank is not
  the bottleneck.
- **Do NOT fold more pairs onto the existing adapter.** Catastrophic
  forgetting risk with LoRA is real (Kwon 2024 on Qwen2.5-1.5B specifically);
  more pairs at LR 5e-5 on top of a trained adapter tends to fight existing
  weights.
- **Do NOT skip attribution and go straight to LIMA.** The LIMA design
  decision Alfred asked about ('sort in proportion to data OR effect?') has
  a THIRD answer — sort by MEASURED influence, which requires attribution.

## Fold-gate check

Per user-memory doctrine (Motoi training config LOCKED):
- Base Qwen2.5-Coder-1.5B-Instruct : PRESERVED in all paths
- LoRA rank 128                    : PRESERVED — Q2 verdict
- Seq len 4096                     : PRESERVED
- Odd prime seed (31)              : PRESERVED
- Output version 0.75              : this recommendation targets 0.76 or 0.8, NOT 1.0
- Notify Alfred via AskUserQuestion at fold gate : deferred to Alfred's call

## Confidence

- Q1 recommendation table: HIGH confidence on ranking, MEDIUM on M2 Max
  timing estimates (haven't profiled DataInf on Apple Silicon; may need CPU
  fallback for Hessian ops).
- Q2 no-rank-bump verdict: HIGH confidence. Multiple independent studies
  agree.
- Q3 10k-would-have-worked verdict: MEDIUM-HIGH confidence. Direction is
  clear; exact ceiling numbers are estimates.
- Synthesis expected-outcome numbers: MEDIUM. Order-of-magnitude right,
  point estimates are informed guesses."

  :cross-cutting-caveats
"# Cross-cutting caveats

1. **Motoi is offline-hermetic** (per user memory HARD CONSTRAINT). All
   attribution and diagnostic work runs LOCALLY on M2 Max. No API-based
   evaluation, no cloud gradient services. DataInf's ykwon0407 repo is
   local-runnable — verified.

2. **The 70-probe AUDIT-9 suite IS the ground truth for 'effect we want'** —
   any DataInf run uses those 70 probes as the target queries. If Alfred
   wants a different definition of effect, the probe suite has to change
   FIRST, and DataInf re-runs against the new probes.

3. **The evaluation-judge undercounting on verb-recall** (27% raw vs 60–70%
   direct-probe corrected) means Q2 saturation analysis is defended by the
   CORRECTED number, not the raw. If the raw number is closer to truth,
   the rank-capacity argument still holds (Nanney 2025 utilisation numbers
   are architecture-general, not task-specific).

4. **Safety at 0–7% is the load-bearing risk.** Per user memory (Motoi SAFETY
   REFUSALS HARD SAFETY LOCK), 7 refusal categories must fire consistently.
   Any LIMA polish MUST allocate at least 200 pairs to safety refusals with
   near-identical templates for the crisis/emergency categories. Consistency
   IS the safety feature.

5. **The 'STOP fake-completion cycle' feedback** (per user memory) applies
   here: this report describes what a FIX would look like — it does not
   claim anything is fixed. Alfred's decision, Alfred's execution."

